 may I leave the table? And - the grace was said before we lifted a knife or fork, the stuff was all on the table for the - my father would say the grace - before meals. Aye. I mean - he used to say, thank God for that meal. I - I used to say - I used to 
l
ook at him and I used to think my father's terrible. Oh my, I've got a terrible father. He was so good, and the things he would say - one girl came up one night - our school mate to the door and I opened the door and she said, are you coming out? I - I sa
y
s, what? I - I think I'd be around about eight or nine at that time. And I says, what? I said to my mother, can I get out for a little while? No. I couldn't get out. I wouldn't get out. I wouldn't get out, oh no. I wouldn't get out. We never got out from 
w
e came from school at four o'clock. But it didnae worry. It didnae worry us anything, we were all - as we got up we were all very intelligent, and we knew right from wrong and - not to go - people that we shouldn't go with and everything, we were - we wer
enae going - there were not one of us went into any company. Not one of us. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15823640 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
