Oh, we had to. Yes, we had to have table manners and everything and - if - if we want 
a - or anything - we - we would ask for it, like in the summertime, she would say - she would say, it's your turn to go out today. You get out tomorrow. And we had to go out and came in the way we went out, no trouble. Nothing. We got out for about an hou
r or two and that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15823640 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 How did you have to behave towards your parents? Respectfully?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15232123 KS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 
Oh we'd to - sit there and - and - my father was a great reader at night of the paper and that you know. But my mother was a great - she sewed all by hand, 
she wasn't a tailoress but she made her own - pillowslips, and the white sheets, know what it was worth, I believe - there's a woman over there said her mother done the same thing years ago, flour bags - that you get the flour in. And she washed them and 
t
hen she - soaked them in baking soda to take the - the flour - thing off it and the numbers on it, and rolled them up and that and let them stay for two days, then she washed them all out, and that, and boiled them. She made her own - pillowslips. White s
heets, and her own aprons. Flour bags, my cousin said that. She said your mother was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12853325\charrsid7227600 a immaculate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 . We are all the same. That - the - the women down the stair there - Mrs Riley - and she's came up to me - and Miss -
