. She was - night school. But - she was sixteen then. And she went to night school, because - it was during the second world war - and - Liz - Lizzie - no, the first world war, no, it wasn't the s
econd world war, she was over in America at that time, the first world war, and she was going with the telegrams - with the soldiers - that were away abroad send to their mothers or their - people - money and - the telegrams you know, wired, well Lizzie k
n
ew what - the much money was in these wires, so one night - we were in Nanson Street staying then, and - Lizzie came up and my father God rest him he was in bed, and I opened the door and - she came running in. So I said, what's the matter? Oh she says, m
y
 goodness - there's somebody following me, she said, and she said, I've got to go by - by that - up - for Herald Road, and over the Canal Bank to deliver these - telegrams, and she said - I'm terrified of my life. My father said, what? So my father said, 
a
ll right, and he said - just go into the big - room - go into the the kitchen, my father slept in the big room with my brother, so went to the kitchen, my father got his clothes on and he - he didn't take time to put socks on put the shoes on, away with L
i
zzie so he said to me, he took a great big belt out with him, and he said, now you'll walk in front but I'll be at your back. And if he'd have seen a policeman there he would have told him right enough, but he didn't see any of them and on duty. So he wal
k
ed Lizze waked - and my father at her back. And she went right over and - he was there following but he didn't know that - my father who he was and - he was watching Lizzie you know. My father just kept walking at her back but he - he kept walking then he
 
- at my father's back you see but my father - oh my father likely would have - thingmied the belt, he would have used to probably. 'Cos he was very quick tempered. Well anyway - Lizzie got over the canal bank and - that was that. So here - when Lizzie wen
t then - there was a wee sub-post office up there, at the Roundtoll, it's there yet, the Roundtoll but the post office is not, and the head - the head - man up there was Pat Conway - from the General. So Lizzie told }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12853325\charrsid7227600 him}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600  what happened, he lifted the phone an
d phoned this CID. He said, your father didn't do that Lizzie? She said, oh no. My father had to get up out of bed and come along with me, otherwise - I might have been thrown in the canal and the - the money orders that's in the pouch here taken off me. 
I
'd to go up and get my father to - come up with me, I was terrified. Would you know him again? Lizzie said, yes. Well - the detectives were out after him but they never - they never got any trace of him. 'Cos she was sent to - different streets each day y
ou know with the telegrams but they kept looking for him but they never got h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12853325\charrsid7227600 im. But he never harmed Lizzie \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 cos my father was there you see, so she never forgot that, well - she learned - book keeping, typewriting and shorthand and she was going into the General to go behind the counter, then.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15823640 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1067686\charrsid7227600 What age was Lizzie when she went to night school?
