t was beautiful. I thought - I don't know how much it was, it wasn't dear in these days. Not the way it is now. Well - I - I had a - a drop head sewing machine, my father. Yes. He bought it, and - it come in handy although he never made - much clothes for
 
us, my aunts did it. Well - we would have made Anne's dress too, but - they didn't do it, my father never gave them word down, they said that, that some of Lizzie and me should have went down and told them. They would have made it you see. Well anyway - m
y father got that flouncing. Well he was up on his feet - for four in the morning to take the Corporation on at five o'clock and then he - he - he didn't finish 'til four in the day, and then go from that to the picture house in Pickards, at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Seymour Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} 
there to twelve at night. When he came home - I - I gave him something to eat, and he took his jacket off and he got the sewing machine out and he took the length of Anne and all, and he got the material out, he stayed up all night. And he never went to b
ed. And he made that dress for Anne for her first communion. That's what my father did. Yes, she did it.
