Aye. He could but he didn't need do it with my aunts, they said - he worked hard enough with the two jobs, and they - they started to give us our clothes for - well I was so high, right up. But then when they went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, my father didna do much tailoring with the two jobs, but if we needed - frock or that my father made them. The way they did with th
e material, he bought the material and made them. Aye, well that - that was that. But for jackets, he - he never made the jackets, no. 'Cos he'd too much contend with the two jobs but he bought them, but they had to be the best material. Oh - what - and w
e
 went into a shoe shop to go our shoes - the girl used to say, there they are, my father says, what? Bring something more. And he had all the boxes in the shop down, and I used to sit and I was sweating and I - I darena say I wasn't you know, and he would
 
say oh no, I want - a decent pair of shoes, not paper. I'm paying for them he would say, and - and they would have the - the girl had all the boxes down to suit it, what - we - he - oh my - he - I used to be terrified - dread - I dreaded that was it, goin
g with my - say, he'll - he'll make the girl - he'll pull all the - boxes down and the - up on the shelves to get what suited him. Oh he was terrible that way. He -
