Yes, she was a great sewer you know, but - not the frocks that my aunts made 'cos we'd too many of them that she didn't need to do it. We could cha
nge all the time. And what we wore through the week we never had on on a Sunday. We'd special dresses for the winter. One time - they got blue serge, oh it was beautiful. And it was a box pleat, back and front, and the pleats, oh it must have took them - 
i
t didn't take them, they were like that, all in - and they come in like - talk about a kilt. And they were all like that, well - they were light blue. Oh they were beautiful, and went to Mass then in the winter with them and nice jackets on as - and all a
n
d the teachers used to look, and she used to say Lizzie and me, come here Lizzie, Kathy. Says - the one teacher said to the other, look at that. She said, they're the best kept children here that go to mass. But my teacher said - and so did Lizzie's, but 
-
 their aunts are pure dressmakers. Their aunts are born dressmakers. That's why. But they said - their mother takes in a pride in them and all, we'd long hair and I had jet black hair, away down to here. Well - when we went to school - it - my mother plai
t
ed them, and I had ribbon on to here. Lizzie was the same. Well the only time we got the hair out - was when we went to Mass on a Sunday and down to see my aunts in Partick. She wouldn't let our hair go loose the way they're going the now. Oh no. She was 
v
ery particular that way. She was, she really took a pride in us. We - well we - we took the long hair after her. We did. But - she was jet black and - Lizzie took the fairness off my father. My father said - one day - when we washed our own hair and that 
as we grew bigger you see. So he said, do you know what I shampooed my hair with? I said, no da. He said - the white of an egg. So I - I looked at him. I was mesmerised. I says, what da? Oh my goodness, I said, the people in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} here would be looking f
or to eat it never mind put it on your hair. And he laughed at me, aye, that was what he put in his hair, he shampooed his hair with. He was very very particular. And he was a man - I washed all his shirts, oh aye, they were thoroughly washed as I grew up
,
 and he used to say, now - get me a week box that had borax - borax. So I said, da, what do you want that for? He - he said you'll soon see. So he would - get the hot water and damp the collar of the - shirt and the cuffs. Damp them. Then he would make up
 
the borax in hot water, and - put the neck of the shirt into it and - and the - cuffs, and he - I had to hang it on the pulley for a wee while to dry. And then he would say, now, get the - iron out, the electric iron out and I would say, da, I'll iron the
m
. No, I'll do them myself he used to say, but watch. Just stand there and look. And then you'll know how it's done. So he says, now - what do you see that the borax has done to the cuffs and the - the collar? I said, it glosses. Well he says, that's the w
ay I want it. So - that shows he was a very particular man. Ay? Aye?
